# Normalize ADT

# Calculate baseline:

#  http://bioconductor.org/books/3.16/OSCA.advanced/integrating-with-protein-abundance.html#control-based-normalization
control_sf <- scater::librarySizeFactors(altExp(norm_sce), subset_row=controls)  # `controls` was previously defined during filtering
sum(control_sf == 0)/length(control_sf) # _HOLY WOW_ - virtually everything is 0.......

0.2 Dimension reduction

HVGs:

num_genes <- 5000 # 2000? 

gene_variance <- scran::modelGeneVar(norm_sce)
hvg_list <- scran::getTopHVGs(gene_variance,
                               n = num_genes)

PCA:

# Do we want to set the number of PCs?
norm_sce <- scater::runPCA(norm_sce,
                           subset_row = hvg_list)

UMAP:

# Perform graph clustering first
nn_k <- 15
nn_clusters <- clusterRows(
  reducedDim(norm_sce, "PCA"), 
  NNGraphParam(k = nn_k, 
               cluster.fun = "walktrap")
)

# pop back into sce
norm_sce$nn_clusters <- factor(nn_clusters)

# Add in UMAPs and plot with colors
norm_sce <- scater::runUMAP(norm_sce,
                            dimred = "PCA")
scater::plotReducedDim(norm_sce, "UMAP", colour_by = "nn_clusters")

# The top 5 cell types account for over 98% of the cells!
celltype_counts %>%
  dplyr::slice(1:5) %>%
  dplyr::summarize(sum(n) / sum(celltype_counts$n))

top_celltypes <- as.character(celltype_counts$celltype[1:5]) 

# Recode a new celltype vector with top 5 separated from "other" using some forcats magic
norm_sce$celltype_predictions_top <- forcats::fct_lump_n(norm_sce$celltype_predictions, 5)

                       point_alpha = 0.6, point_size = 0.25)

0.4 ADT “celltyping”

We can leverage the ADTs as protein markers to identify likely celltypes, which can be compared back to the SingleR annotations as a form of validation.

# What are the proteins?
rownames(altExp(norm_sce))
 [1] "CD3"   "CD4"   "CD8"   "CD11c" "CD14"  "CD16"  "CD19"  "CD56"  "CD45"  "IgG1" 
# Which ADT is the most prevalent for each cell? 
max_adt_indices <- apply(
  logcounts(altExp(norm_sce)),
  2,
  which.max
)
max_adt <- rownames(altExp(norm_sce))[max_adt_indices]

unique(max_adt)
[1] "CD4"   "CD14"  "CD19"  "CD3"   "CD11c" "CD16"  "CD56"  "CD8"  
# Add this into the main SCE experiment for UMAPing
norm_sce$max_adt <- max_adt


# Misc thinking...how can we quantify this?
## ratio of biggest:\sum(rest)?
## difference between highest and next highest?

Happily, none of these is the control! What are these proteins, and what celltypes might they indicate? In the source quotes below, I have added the bold to the celltypes.

  • CD3
    • “CD3 (cluster of differentiation 3) is a protein complex and T cell co-receptor that is involved in activating both the cytotoxic T cell (CD8+ naive T cells) and T helper cells (CD4+ naive T cells). … This high specificity, combined with the presence of CD3 at all stages of T-cell development, makes it a useful immunohistochemical marker for T-cells in tissue sections.” source
  • CD4
    • TCR co-receptor that we can probably assume is mostly on CD4+ T-cells
  • CD8
    • TCR co-receptor that we can probably assume is mostly on CD8+ T-cells
  • CD11c
    • “CD11c is a type I transmembrane protein that is expressed on monocytes, granulocytes, a subset of B cells, dendritic cells, and macrophages and may be demonstrated on B-cell chronic lymphocytic leukemia, marginal zone lymphomas, and hairy cell leukemia.” source
  • CD14
    • “CD14 is a glycolipid-anchored membrane glycoprotein expressed on cells of the myelomonocyte lineage including monocytes, macrophages, and some granulocytes.” source
  • CD16
    • “CD16 is involved in antibody-dependent cell-mediated cytotoxicity and is expressed on large granular lymphocytes (LGLs) of both NK- and T-cell types.” source
  • CD19
    • “CD19 is an IgSF surface glycoprotein of 95 kDa that is expressed from the earliest stages of B cell development until plasma cell terminal differentiation, when its expression is lost.” source
  • CD56
    • “CD56 expression is also found in, among others, the hematopoietic system. Here, the expression of CD56 is mostly associated with, but not limited to, natural killer cells. CD56 has been detected on other lymphoid cells, including gamma delta Τ cells and activated CD8+ T cells, as well as on dendritic cells.” source

Let’s color cells by their most prevalent ADT:
